description.plain:
Making waves with his witty lyrical style and down-to-earth sense of humor and personality, Jack Harlow shot to the top of the charts off the back of that very charisma. Born on March 13, 1998 in Louisville, Kentucky, Harlow released his first official project in 2014 titled Finally Handsome, as well as an EP the following year which kickstarted his drive to make music.

After racking up around 250,000 total views on YouTube as of 2016, his 2017 project, Gazebo, was immediately met with a very positive reaction by fans and celebrities alike; launching his career to another platform. “Dark Knight”—the second song released off the album—eventually featured on the front page of Worldstar Hip-Hop and racked up 1,000,000+ views on YouTube. Additionally, he even got a co-sign for the aforementioned song from both Peter Rosenberg and fellow Louisville native Bryson Tiller.

Harlow is now associated with DJ Drama and Don Cannon’s Generation Now record label. In 2018, he released Loose. Harlow’s fourth official project and his first major release since signing with Generation Now and Atlantic Records, the project was a showcase of his increasing stardom, as he managed to get rap veteran CyHi The Prynce and former XXL Freshman K Camp to feature on the project. That same year, Harlow was even a guest performer at Genius' very own IQ/BBQ. Jack was later named to the 2020 XXL Freshman list, himself.

Harlow made his mainstream breakthrough in 2020 off the back of his single “WHATS POPPIN”, a wordplay and pop culture reference-filled track bolstered by a Cole Bennett-directed music video on Lyrical Lemonade. The track reached new heights when its success spawned a remix featuring DaBaby, Tory Lanez, and Lil Wayne. The song would go on to peak at #2 on the Billboard Hot 100.

The song became the lead single off of his debut studio album, Thats What They All Say, which peaked at #5 on the Billboard 200, was certified Platinum by the RIAA, and spawned the Platinum single “Tyler Herro” and the Big Sean-featuring Gold single “Way Out”, which peaked at #34 and #74, respectively, on the Hot 100.

Harlow’s success only continued to climb in the lead-up to his second studio album, Come Home The Kids Miss You. Harlow featured on Lil Nas X’s smash hit “Industry Baby”, which would go on to become Harlow’s first number one single on the Hot 100 and be certified 4x Platinum by the RIAA. The hype surrounding this collaboration bolstered Harlow’s profile, carrying over into the first two singles off of his second studio album: “Nail Tech” and “First Class”. While the former peaked at #18, the latter was an instant hit, becoming Harlow’s second #1 single and his first to debut at the top spot.

songs.title: First Class

description.plain:
Following the success of “Nail Tech,” the lead single from his album Come Home The Kids Miss You, released on February 18 – Jack Harlow delivers his second release of 2022 with an R&B-influence production.

Harlow first teased the song in a Instagram post  during the making of the album and officially released it on April 8. The full LP would be available a month later on May 6, 2022.

The song samples Fergie’s 2007 hit “Glamorous,” especially the pre-chorus, where Fergie sings:

G-L-A-M-O-R-O-U-S, yeah
G-L-A-M-O-R-O-U-S

songs.title: Tyler Herro

description.plain:
Fresh off his 2020 XXL Freshman nomination, Jack Harlow pays homage to friend and NBA player Tyler Herro—with whom he is pictured on the single’s cover. The song marks Harlow’s first solo release since his chart-topping remix of his breakout hit “WHATS POPPIN” and is the first single of his debut album Thats What They All Say.

“Tyler Herro” surfaced online ten days prior to its official release on October 22, 2020, alongside a music video starring friends Harlow and Herro.

songs.title: Churchill Downs

description.plain:
“Churchill Downs” is the first collaboration between Drake and Jack Harlow. The song is named after a famous racecourse in Jack’s hometown of Louisville, Kentucky.

The duo spit introspective bars over a smooth beat, updating their own lives to listeners through their storytelling.

The track’s instrumental, although unknown until after its leak, was previewed on Jack Harlow’s Instagram on March 15, 2022. The snippet featured many muted clips of him in the studio and performing. The song was officially released along with the album with an extended verse from Jack.

The duo spit introspective bars over a smooth beat, updating their own lives to listeners through their storytelling.

The track’s instrumental, although unknown until after its leak, was previewed on Jack Harlow’s Instagram on March 15, 2022. The snippet featured many muted clips of him in the studio and performing. The song was officially released along with the album with an extended verse from Jack.

songs.title: Nail Tech

description.plain:
“Nail Tech” is Louisville native Jack Harlow’s first release of 2022. Following a sparse 2021, which left Jack’s next release to be highly anticipated, the track boasts lyrics about Jack’s material gain, including chains, designer brands, and cars. He also brings back themes of critics doubting him despite his high status.

Jack first announced the song’s release date in an Instagram video: then, a few days later, he officially revealed its title in another post. A final teaser was released just hours before the song was released.

songs.title: SUNDOWN

description.plain: Sundown was released around the time that Jack moved to Atlanta. He describes listening to a lot of Clipse, and 2forwOyNE put a beat together, after Don Cannon gained permission from Pharrell Williams, sampling Hell Hath No Fury intro track We Got It for Cheap. Two versions of the song were made, with Harlow combining them into the version of Sundown that we have today. The track was the lead single off of Loose, and propelled Jack’s career.

Two versions of the song were made, with Harlow combining them into the version of Sundown that we have today. The track was the lead single off of Loose, and propelled Jack’s career.

songs.full_title: THRU THE NIGHT by Jack Harlow (Ft. Bryson Tiller)
songs.title: THRU THE NIGHT

description.plain:
“Thru the Night” was the first single released from Jack Harlow in anticipation of his 2019 mixtape Confetti. The track features fellow Louisville native Bryson Tiller rapping alongside Harlow over a sample from Usher’s “U Don’t Have To Call.”

In an interview with Billboard, Harlow touched on what it was like getting Tiller to hop on the track:

I was in Las Vegas with [DJ] Drama, and Bryson’s assistant was there with us. Bryson and I have been cool on social media, but we’ve never had any direct contact. In the club I told her, “I got a record.” The next morning, she texted me, “Don’t forget to send me that song.” I sent it, and then he DM’d me saying it was hard. He didn’t do it right away, but I saw him at [the Kentucky] Derby and was like, “Yo, I’m ready for that verse. I got a project coming.” He knocked it out after we saw each other in person, and then we got to chop it up for real.

songs.title: WARSAW

description.plain:
Warsaw is the fifth song of the 12-track mixtape Confetti, bringing together Jack Harlow and 2forwOyNE, Jack’s childhood buddy and in-house producer.

The music video was the 4th clip released off of this mixtape and has over 4M views on Youtube. It was also directed by one of Jack’s Private Garden crew member, Ace Pro, and shot in Jack’s hometown of Louisville, KY.

songs.title: Side Piece

description.plain:
“Side Piece” is the sixth cut on Louisville rapper Jack Harlow’s album, “Come Home The Kids Miss You.”

It samples Snoop Dogg’s 2002 song, Beautiful. It features two parts, divided by a beat switch. This is reminiscent of his 2020 track, 21C / Delta, which also mingles with the idea of his relationships with women.

Harlow mentioned on Twitter that the second half of the song was originally named “Blow A Kiss”.

songs.title: Face of My City
songs.title_with_featured: Face of My City (Ft. Lil Baby)

description.plain:
Jack Harlow and Lil Baby stand as ‘faces’ of their respective hometowns of Louisville and Atlanta on their first collaboration. “Face Of My City” comes after both artists had a huge 2020, and only one month after Lil Baby announced that would quit doing features to focus on his upcoming third studio album.

Throughout the song, the two rappers celebrate their success and contemplate their rise to major figures in their cities. Both artists are no stranger to representing their hometowns in their music: Baby has rapped about “putting on for Atlanta” before, while Harlow expressed how he went from underdog to self-proclaimed ‘hometown hero’ on his 2020 XXL Freshmen Cypher:

City used to hate, but I made y'all fans

The producer we know for working with the likes of Kendrick Lamar,  DJ Dahi, has a chill beat for Jack Harlow to rap on with a low-key voice.

songs.title: Rendezvous

description.plain:
On the legendary producer Hit-Boy song “Rendezvous”, Jack Harlow brings up about his massive come up in 2020 and how we became wealthy overcoming the all odds. The track contains only a verse from him, without no hook, which he mentions in the lyrics too.

The song samples the track Lost For Words by Midnight Movers, which was also sampled in Wiz Khalifa’s song “Favorite Show” featuring Boogz Boogetz.

songs.full_title: Same Guy by Jack Harlow (Ft. Adam Levine)
songs.title: Same Guy

description.plain:
“Same Guy” is a smooth, funky playboy anthem that feels like a track you’d listen to on a thoughtful, somber drive home from a… “friend’s” house.

Jack alludes to the mistakes he has made and the time he has wasted in his personal life as his star has risen over the years. He acknowledges that he needs to straighten up, but the temptations of the superstar lifestyle haven’t been easy to resist.

Harlow enlists Adam Levine for background vocals throughout the track, uniquely deploying the Maroon 5 frontman’s voice as an instrument of sorts over this jetsonmade’s production.

songs.title: Eastern Parkway

description.plain:
Eastern Parkway is the first song off of Jack Harlow’s third official project, Gazebo. Its title is a reference to the road that runs through the city of Louisville, connecting the University of Louisville to the Highlands and ending a few blocks from Southern Parkway.

The album is intentionally influenced heavily by the city of Louisville, as Jack stated he wanted to make something that, “Sounded like Louisville at night”.

songs.title: Baxter Avenue

description.plain:
On “Baxter Avenue,” Jack Harlow pays respect to his hometown Louisville, Kentucky.

Baxter Avenue is a main street in the Highlands section of the city that is home to some of Harlow’s favorite places to eat and near where he went to Highlands Middle School.

Harlow details family members, friends and what he used to go growing up before he reached his heights in the rap game.

songs.title: State Fair

description.plain:
The final track on Come Home The Kids Miss You follows Jack’s traditional formula of a no-hook introspective freestyle with a title dedicated to a location in his home state of Kentucky, as seen on previous closing cuts such as RIVER ROAD and Baxter Avenue.

On the track, he reflects on dealing with his rapid ascension and adaptation to stardom, as well as his aspirations for his continued rise in future.

songs.title: HEAVY HITTER

description.plain:
Harlow created hype for this song prior to its release by creating a one-minute snippet of the song on Instagram on April 7, 2019.  Five months later, one day before the song’s official release date, the same snippet was released on Harlow’s Twitter. However, this version of the snippet was accompanied by a music video:

https://twitter.com/jackharlow/status/1173404674399133696?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Etweet

The full song and music video were eventually released the following day as the second single off the mixtape, CONFETTI.

body.plain: RIVER ROAD is one of Harlow’s most impressive, yet overlooked pieces. A 4-minute song with no hook or repeating lyrics, only Jack reminiscing about his childhood and thinking about his future.

songs.lyrics:

[Verse 2]

Two years in ATL

That they only ever get a chance to see on they TL
Artists that they playing through a JBL

songs.title: Detox

description.plain: Serving as the fifth track of Gazebo, Detox is a letter to Jack’s age group, providing a direct sense of relatability and understanding. According to a 2018 interview with SpecialSays, the song was written with 2forwOyNE and Nemo Achida, the latter of which provided backing vocals and provided Jack with the concept for the song.

songs.title: Automatic

description.plain:
Automatic is Harlow’s contribution to the Madden NFL 21 soundtrack, and his first release since being named a XXL Freshman for 2020. A snippet of the song was first heard in the game’s official reveal trailer. The cover art incorporates a play diagram design, paying homage to the track’s primary medium. On SoundCloud, the track is listed as having been released on June 19, 2020, though this is obviously untrue. In a Tweet from June, Jack reported that this song would be a collaboration with The Cool Kids rapper Chuck Inglish, who produced the instrumental.

songs.title: SUNDAY NIGHT

description.plain: “Sunday Night”, from Jacks third official mixtape, “Confetti”, proves to me the most focused song on the project in terms of story and idea. Jack describes the feeling of missing what seems to be an ex girlfriend, despite doing fine without her until this point. This is evident from the chorus “I was doing pretty good without you, but something tells me that a relapse’s coming”. Jack fights the urge to text her as he desperately wants to know what’s going on in her life. He wants to detach from her completely, but still can’t help but wonder what her current relationship status is, or if she found someone new. He knows it’ll cause him harm to know the truth, but just can’t help wanting to know. Jack knows what’s best for him to move on, but this new wave of pain and heartbreak is leaving him teetering.

songs.title: Larry Bird

description.plain: Larry Joe Bird is a former professional basketball player, coach, and NBA executive, regarded as one of the greatest basketball players of all time, perhaps most notable for his time playing with the Celtics; various basketball references are dropped throughout. The latter half of the track is a false advertisement, as “Music for the Deaf,” the project that he likely refers to in the outro, was never released.

body.plain: An early track released before The Handsome Harlow EP, Top of the Morning was one of the many tracks purged by Harlow in an attempt to maintain his current persona. The only evidence of this track’s existence is a snippet posted to Facebook in October 2015. It was produced by Private Garden and The Homies member Ace Pro.

That's why reefer stay in my lungs/
Westside negro, pay my funds/

Leave a mess when I'm reconnecting my pieces (yes sir), peep finesse/

& Then they heard we, yes, The Assembly, proceed to drop heat in sentences/

I wish to bless thee this season, yes?/
